41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.330b5502-a98f-43b7-a26c-174b61e3474d.description=
This operation loops as many times as specified in the "count" input, counting from "1" to a greater number, incrementing it by "1" at each iteration.

Inputs\:
    count - The number of loops to complete.
Valid values\: from 1 to 9223372036854775807
    reset - Specifies whether the counter restarts counting from "1".
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    to - The number to count to. It will take the value of the "count" input field. 
    from - The number to start counting at. For this operation, it is customized to "1".
    incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. For this operation, it is customized to "1".

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the value of the number that was just counted.

Responses\:
    has more – The counting process is not complete. One or more iterations are pending.
    no more – The counting process is complete.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
1. It is recommended that you do not change the values of the "to", "from" or "incrementBy" input fields.
2. The "from", "to" and "incrementBy" inputs are customized for this operation. Even though you can also customize them, if you need to specify the loop range borders and the increment value, use the "Counter" operation.

Examples\:
1. For a loop with 20 iterations, the following values should be provided for the input fields\:
    count\: 20
    reset\: false (this field can also be left blank, as "false" is the default value)
2. For an infinite loop, the value of "count" should be at least "1" and the value of "reset" should be "true".
41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.479a8b69-fcc9-4693-b8c9-b9335702fac2.prompt=d64b020e-d3ca-47ce-9cf9-a65606679aad.82f33961-7bdc-42f4-af21-ed686fbd6db9.prompt 41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.73e6b1fd-0d12-4208-9185-931cbaceec73.description=d64b020e-d3ca-47ce-9cf9-a65606679aad.91ef3da5-6b92-4761-86bd-489b121c8c72.description 41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.99a29cad-a7cc-4f95-a289-6fc948bcc06c.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
    Current date and time.

Responses\:
    success - Date/time retrieved successfully.   
    failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.

Notes.
    1. If localeLang is 'unix' the localeCountry input is ignored and the result will be the current UNIX timestamp.
41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.acf869ff-7e69-40d5-aad4-048db74dab29.description=
This operation waits for the number of seconds specified in the "seconds" input.

Inputs\:
    seconds - The number of seconds to wait.

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the "completed sleep" message if the operation completed successfully and an error message otherwise. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.bdfb1d02-00e0-49d3-a7d1-7345425a12d7.prompt=d64b020e-d3ca-47ce-9cf9-a65606679aad.2715c46d-ca90-44d9-ad8d-ed5ba8f081fc.prompt 41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.c6b4e154-6072-4399-a8f7-a918acc947ac.description=
Sends an smtp email
 
Input Parameters\:
hostname - hostname or ip address of smtp server
port - port smtp service is listening
from - from email address
to - email address(s) or recipients
subject - email subject
body - body of the email
htmlEmail - true or false, whether the email should be sent supporting html rich email.
readReceipt - true or false, whether or not to request a read receipt
attachments - comma separated list of files to attach (must be full path)
username - if SMTP authentication is needed, the username to send
password - the password to use
characterSet - the character set encoding for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is UTF-8
contentTransferEncoding - the content transfer encoding scheme (such as 7bit, 8bit, base64, quoted-printable etc) for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is - quoted-printable or Q Encoding.
 
 Responses\:
 success - successfully sent the email
 failure - failed to send the email

Note\:
For special characters (East Asian, right-to-left languages, etc.) you must install the support files on your local machine.
	For doing this on Windows go to Control Panel -> Regional and Language Options -> Language and check the options at Supplemental language support.
41cd93b3-21e7-4a27-a24a-185b0344489c.e04d46f1-ab65-4769-9b9d-9cbe04c9edf3.description=
Runs a SQL command against an Oracle database, using the information available in the tnsnames.ora file.   
Does not return any results (only whether the command was executed)

Input Parameters\:
TNSPath - The path to the parent folder of the TNS file which contains the DB connecting info(the name of the DB server, the port used for connecting to the DB server, the database name)
TNSEntry - the entry name from the tnsnames.ora file which contains the connecting information
Username - username to connect as
Password - password
Command - the command to execute

Responses\:
more items - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
updateCount - the update count of the command executed

NOTE\: 
This op supports only Oracle. The tnsnames.ora file should correctly configured on the RAS machine.

ORACLE NOTE\:
It is possible to run PL/SQL procedures using this operation. The examples below present the syntax to be used for having the same effect as the following PL/SQL script\:
BEGIN
  send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');
END;

Example 1\: BEGIN send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');END;

Example 2\: BEGIN send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test');END;

Example 3\: {CALL send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test')}

Example 4\: {CALL send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test')}
